data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler binds `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based calls, so it throws at runtime.

## Fix options

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). Use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` for those cases.
